# Reading Context Value

The easiest way to consume context in a functional component is the `useContext` hook.

```jsx
import { useContext } from 'react';
import { UserContext } from './UserContext';

function Profile() {
  const user = useContext(UserContext);
  return <p>{user.name}</p>;
}
```

This component will re-render whenever the context value changes.

## Without Hooks (Class Components)

You can also use `Context.Consumer` with a render prop, but `useContext` is much cleaner.

slides.codeSnippet:
// UserContext.js
import { createContext } from 'react';
export const UserContext = createContext();

// App.js
import { UserContext } from './UserContext';
import Profile from './Profile';

function App() {
  const user = { name: 'Alice' };
  return (
    <UserContext.Provider value={user}>
      <Profile />
    </UserContext.Provider>
  );
}

// Profile.js
import { useContext } from 'react';
import { UserContext } from './UserContext';

export default function Profile() {
  const user = useContext(UserContext);
  return <h1>Hello, {user.name}!</h1>;
}
